=========================================================
STATIC MEMBERS IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
Static members are class members that belong to the CLASS itself rather
than to individual objects.

There are two types:

1. Static Data Members
2. Static Member Functions

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED STATIC MEMBERS?
=========================================================

Normally:

Each object gets its own copy of non-static data members.

Example:

class Test
{
    int x;
};

Test t1, t2;

Memory:

t1 -> x
t2 -> x

Two copies of x exist.

Sometimes we need a variable shared by ALL objects.

Examples:
• Number of objects created
• Application configuration
• Global counters
• Shared resources

Static members solve this problem.

=========================================================
1. STATIC DATA MEMBER
=========================================================

Definition:
A static data member is shared among all objects of a class.
Only ONE copy exists in memory.

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Test
{
public:
    static int count;
};

int Test::count = 0;

int main()
{
    Test t1;
    Test t2;

    t1.count++;
    t2.count++;

    cout << Test::count;
}

Output:
2

Reason:
Only one shared copy exists.

=========================================================
MEMORY REPRESENTATION
=========================================================

Non-static:

t1 -> x
t2 -> x
t3 -> x

Three copies.

---------------------------------------------------------

Static:

Test::count

Only one copy.

t1 ----|
t2 ----|----> count
t3 ----|

=========================================================
CHARACTERISTICS OF STATIC DATA MEMBERS
=========================================================

1. Shared by all objects.
2. Memory allocated only once.
3. Exists even if no object is created.****************
4. Belongs to class, not object.
5. Stored in Static/Data Segment.
6. Can be accessed using class name.

=========================================================
DECLARATION AND DEFINITION
=========================================================

Inside class:

class Test
{
public:
    static int count;
};

Outside class:

int Test::count = 0;

=========================================================
WHY DEFINITION OUTSIDE CLASS?
=========================================================

Inside class:

static int count;

Only declaration.

Memory is allocated by:

int Test::count = 0;
IMP********
static data members are declared inside the class but defined outside the class because only the definition allocates memory. 
Accessing a static member without its definition results in a linker error (undefined reference).

=========================================================
ACCESSING STATIC MEMBERS
=========================================================

Preferred:

cout << Test::count;

Allowed:

Test t;
cout << t.count;

Preferred:
Use ClassName::member.

=========================================================
REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Employee
{
public:
    static int totalEmployees;

    Employee()
    {
        totalEmployees++;
    }
};

int Employee::totalEmployees = 0;

=========================================================
2. STATIC MEMBER FUNCTION
=========================================================

Definition:
A function that belongs to the class rather than objects.

Declared using:

static

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    static void display()
    {
        cout << "Hello";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Test::display();
}

Output:
Hello

=========================================================
CHARACTERISTICS OF STATIC MEMBER FUNCTIONS
=========================================================

1. Belongs to class.
2. Called using class name.
3. No object required.
4. Has NO this pointer.
5. Can access only static members.

=========================================================
WHY NO this POINTER?
=========================================================

Non-static function:

void fun()
{
}

Compiler internally:

void fun(Test* this);

---------------------------------------------------------

Static function:

static void fun()
{
}

Compiler internally:

void fun();

No object parameter.

Therefore:

No this pointer.

=========================================================
CAN STATIC FUNCTION ACCESS NON-STATIC MEMBERS?
=========================================================

NO.

=========================================================

class Test
{
    int x = 10;

public:
    static void fun()
    {
        cout << x; // ERROR
    }
};

=========================================================

Reason:
Static function has no object and therefore no this pointer.

=========================================================
CAN STATIC FUNCTION ACCESS STATIC MEMBERS?
=========================================================

YES.

=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    static int count;

    static void display()
    {
        cout << count;
    }
};

int Test::count = 100;

=========================================================

=========================================================
STATIC MEMBER FUNCTION CALL
=========================================================

Preferred:

Test::display();

Allowed:

Test t;
t.display();

Preferred:
ClassName::FunctionName()

=========================================================
STATIC MEMBER FUNCTION USE CASES*************
=========================================================

1. Utility Functions
2. Factory Functions
3. Singleton getInstance()
4. Shared Counters
5. Helper Methods

=========================================================
STATIC MEMBER INITIALIZATION (C++17)
=========================================================

Before C++17:

class Test
{
public:
    static int count;
};

int Test::count = 100;

=========================================================

C++17:

class Test
{
public:
    inline static int count = 100;
};

No separate definition required.

Feature:
Inline Variables (C++17)

=========================================================
INTERVIEW QUESTION
=========================================================

Which C++17 feature is this?

Answer:
Inline Variables.

=========================================================
STATIC LOCAL VARIABLE
=========================================================

Definition:
A local variable that retains its value across function calls.

=========================================================

void fun()
{
    static int x = 0;

    x++;

    cout << x << endl;
}

int main()
{
    fun();
    fun();
    fun();
}

Output:

1
2
3

=========================================================

Without static:

1
1
1

=========================================================
LIFETIME VS SCOPE
=========================================================

Static Local Variable:

Scope:
Inside function only.

Lifetime:
Entire program execution.

=========================================================
MEMORY SEGMENT
=========================================================

Static Members and Static Local Variables are stored in:

Static/Data Segment

NOT:

Stack
Heap

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is a static data member?

Answer:
A class variable shared among all objects. Only one copy exists.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. Where are static variables stored?

Answer:
Static/Data Segment.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. How many copies of a static member exist?

Answer:
Only one.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Does static member exist if no object is created?

Answer:
YES.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Why does static function not have this pointer?

Answer:
Because it belongs to the class, not objects.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Can static function access non-static members?

Answer:
NO.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. Can static function access static members?

Answer:
YES.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q8. Can constructors be static?

Answer:
NO.

Reason:
Constructors create objects.
Static functions belong to class and have no object.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q9. Can destructors be static?

Answer:
NO.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q10. Can static functions be virtual?

Answer:
NO.

Reason:
Virtual functions require:

Object
→ vptr
→ vtable

Static functions:
No object
No this pointer

Therefore cannot participate in Runtime Polymorphism.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q11. Can static data members be private?

Answer:
YES.

=========================================================

class Test
{
private:
    static int count;
};

=========================================================

Q12. Can static member functions be overloaded?**********

Answer:
YES.

=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    static void fun()
    {
    }

    static void fun(int)
    {
    }
};

=========================================================

Q13. Are static members inherited?

Answer:
YES.

They are inherited but still only one shared copy exists.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER
=========================================================

Static members belong to the class rather than individual objects.
Static data members have only one shared copy stored in the static/data
segment, while static member functions have no this pointer and can
access only static members. They are commonly used for shared state,
counters, utility methods, and singleton implementations.

=========================================================
1-LINE MEMORY TRICK
=========================================================

static
   ↓
Belongs to Class
   ↓
Single Shared Copy
   ↓
No this Pointer (for static functions)
   ↓
Stored in Static/Data Segment
=========================================================
